<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-707-154  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 707 154.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Engineering Times  July 30 1990 n601 p45(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Critical cues for producing semiconductors in the 1990s.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Appleton, Steve.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Semiconductor manufacturers wanting to quickly deliverhigh-quality, competitively-priced products in the 1990s mustaddress advanced technology costs, equipment automation andemployee organization and education.andP;  Semiconductor productioncosts are rising as companies build $400 million to $500 millioneight-inch wafer fabrication facilities, decrease chip size,reduce impurities and address environmental issues.andP;  Companiesmust make cooperative agreements in order to bear cost increases.andO;Equipment automation to improve productivity includes equipmentintercommunications and automated data collection, analysis andpresentation.andP;  Semiconductor manufacturing employees must beintegrated within product areas to improve communications.andO;Manufacturing is demanding wider knowledge and skills, socompanies must train employees in a variety of skills.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Semiconductor IndustryProductionCapital InvestmentManufacturingInformation Systems.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>